<paragraph blockId="18.[135,1091,335,1067]" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">
Diagnosis 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[325,339,336,362]" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">–</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Varga &amp; Gyulai &amp; Ronkay &amp; Ronkay" authorityYear="2018" box="[343,626,335,361]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Ctenoceratoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mallopyga">
<emphasis box="[343,626,335,361]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">Ctenoceratoda mallopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is on average the largest and the most colourful member of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Christoph" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[455,538,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mamestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lupa">
<emphasis box="[455,538,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">C. lupa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group (wingspan 
<quantity box="[773,902,369,396]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" metricValueMax="5.1" metricValueMin="4.3" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" unit="mm" value="47.0" valueMax="51.0" valueMin="43.0">43–51 mm</quantity>
) having broad forewing and robust body. Ground colour of body and forewings variably dark whitish-grey, the lighter parts have some bluish shade while the darker parts of the thorax and the forewing are covered with darker graphite-grey scales. The forewing pattern is rather similar throughout the members of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Christoph" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[137,186,537,563]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mamestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lupa">
<emphasis box="[137,186,537,563]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">lupa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group but the colouration is not brownish or ochreous as in the closely related 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pungeler" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[231,383,571,597]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hadula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="contempta">
<emphasis box="[231,383,571,597]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">C. contempta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[402,489,571,597]" captionStart="Figs 17–24" captionStartId="11.[174,219,1420,1442]" captionTargetBox="[183,1118,183,1403]" captionTargetId="figure-20@11.[180,1121,180,1406]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 17–24. Ctenoceratoda spp. 17–19 = Ctenoceratoda mallopyga mallopyga sp. n., 17–18 = paratype, male, Pakistan, 19 = paratype, female, Pakistan, Hindukush Mts; 20 = C. contempta (Püngeler, 1914), lectotypel male, [China, Xinjiang] “Ost-Turkestan, Aksu”; 21 = C. septemlacustris Gaal-Haszler, Lödl, Ronkay, Ronkay &amp; Varga, 2012, holotype, male, Afghanistan, Koh-i-Baba Mts; 22 = C. lupa (Christoph, 1893), lectotype, male, [Iran] Hyrcania, Shahkuh; 23–24 = C. mallopyga dyschroa ssp. n., India, Himachal Pradesh: 23 = holotype, male, 24 =" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5734642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5734642/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Christoph" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[511,595,571,597]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mamestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lupa">
<emphasis box="[511,595,571,597]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">C. lupa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[611,695,571,597]" captionStart="Figs 17–24" captionStartId="11.[174,219,1420,1442]" captionTargetBox="[183,1118,183,1403]" captionTargetId="figure-20@11.[180,1121,180,1406]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 17–24. Ctenoceratoda spp. 17–19 = Ctenoceratoda mallopyga mallopyga sp. n., 17–18 = paratype, male, Pakistan, 19 = paratype, female, Pakistan, Hindukush Mts; 20 = C. contempta (Püngeler, 1914), lectotypel male, [China, Xinjiang] “Ost-Turkestan, Aksu”; 21 = C. septemlacustris Gaal-Haszler, Lödl, Ronkay, Ronkay &amp; Varga, 2012, holotype, male, Afghanistan, Koh-i-Baba Mts; 22 = C. lupa (Christoph, 1893), lectotype, male, [Iran] Hyrcania, Shahkuh; 23–24 = C. mallopyga dyschroa ssp. n., India, Himachal Pradesh: 23 = holotype, male, 24 =" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5734642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5734642/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gaal-Haszler, Lodl, Ronkay, Ronkay &amp; Varga" authorityYear="2012" box="[771,980,571,597]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Ctenoceratoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="septemlacustris">
<emphasis box="[771,980,571,597]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">C. septemlacustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[995,1080,571,597]" captionStart="Figs 17–24" captionStartId="11.[174,219,1420,1442]" captionTargetBox="[183,1118,183,1403]" captionTargetId="figure-20@11.[180,1121,180,1406]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 17–24. Ctenoceratoda spp. 17–19 = Ctenoceratoda mallopyga mallopyga sp. n., 17–18 = paratype, male, Pakistan, 19 = paratype, female, Pakistan, Hindukush Mts; 20 = C. contempta (Püngeler, 1914), lectotypel male, [China, Xinjiang] “Ost-Turkestan, Aksu”; 21 = C. septemlacustris Gaal-Haszler, Lödl, Ronkay, Ronkay &amp; Varga, 2012, holotype, male, Afghanistan, Koh-i-Baba Mts; 22 = C. lupa (Christoph, 1893), lectotype, male, [Iran] Hyrcania, Shahkuh; 23–24 = C. mallopyga dyschroa ssp. n., India, Himachal Pradesh: 23 = holotype, male, 24 =" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5734642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5734642/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) but more bluish or (in worn specimens) slate-grey. The basal part of reniform stigma is more prominently marked with blackish scales than in the related taxa while the claviform stigma is longer and stronger defined with blackish. The crosslines are reduced; the postmedial line is distinctly marked with black arrowheads. Hindwings light grey with darker terminal band.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[135,1091,335,1067]" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">
The male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[436,563,772,799]" captionStart="Figs 47–52" captionStartId="19.[174,219,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[179,1117,209,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-21@19.[179,1121,189,1498]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs 47–52. Ctenoceratoda spp. male genitalia. 47–48 = C. cyanochrea sp. n., paratype, Mongolia, slide No.: RL8644; 49–50 = C. mallopyga mallopyga sp. n., paratype, Pakistan, slide No.: VZ9238; 51–52 = C. contempta (Püngeler, 1914), Semiretshye, slide No.: RL11754" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5734654" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5734654/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">Figs 49, 50</figureCitation>
) are basically similar to those of the related species, but the “head” of the cucullus is relatively larger than in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pungeler" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[932,1084,806,832]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hadula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="contempta">C. contempta</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gaal-Haszler, Lodl, Ronkay, Ronkay &amp; Varga" authorityYear="2012" box="[135,345,839,866]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Ctenoceratoda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="septemlacustris">C. septemlacustris</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Christoph" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[411,496,839,866]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mamestra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lupa">
<emphasis box="[411,496,839,866]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">C. lupa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[511,643,839,866]" captionStart-0="Figs 47–52" captionStart-1="Figs 53–58" captionStartId-0="19.[174,219,1526,1548]" captionStartId-1="20.[136,181,1499,1521]" captionTargetBox-0="[179,1117,209,1493]" captionTargetBox-1="[153,1074,189,1474]" captionTargetId-0="figure-21@19.[179,1121,189,1498]" captionTargetId-1="figure-20@20.[146,1074,189,1478]" captionTargetPageId-0="19" captionTargetPageId-1="20" captionText-0="Figs 47–52. Ctenoceratoda spp. male genitalia. 47–48 = C. cyanochrea sp. n., paratype, Mongolia, slide No.: RL8644; 49–50 = C. mallopyga mallopyga sp. n., paratype, Pakistan, slide No.: VZ9238; 51–52 = C. contempta (Püngeler, 1914), Semiretshye, slide No.: RL11754" captionText-1="Figs 53–58. Ctenoceratoda spp. male genitalia. 53–54 = C. septemlacustris Gaal–Haszler, Lödl, Ronkay, Ronkay et Varga, 2012, paratype, Afghanistan, slide No.: RL10476; 55–56 = C. lupa (Christoph, 1893), Iran, slide No.: RL11753; 57–58 = C. mallopyga dyschroa sp. n., paratype, India Himachal Pradesh, slide No.: VZ9530" figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5734654" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5734656" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5734654/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5734656/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">Figs 51–56</figureCitation>
) and the ampulla is longer and not acute as in the three allied taxa but slightly curved and obtuse terminally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[135,1091,335,1067]" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">
Distribution and bionomics. The new species occurs in the southern Pamirs (Wakhan valley), the eastern Hindukush (east of the Shandur pass), the Karakoram Mts (
<typeStatus box="[393,449,974,1000]" pageId="18" pageNumber="69">type</typeStatus>
locality) and the western Himalayas. It inhabits the medium-high and higher altitudes (between 
<quantity box="[695,856,1008,1034]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="69" unit="m" value="2400.0" valueMax="2800.0" valueMin="2000.0">2000–2800 m</quantity>
), the moths are local but rather frequent in their habitats.
</paragraph>
